ribed dedicatory epigrams, which were compared to pre-Hellenistic dedicatory epigrams in order to highlight the crucial changes that characterise the development of the epigrammatic genre in the Hellenistic era. By demonstrating that the evolution of the epigrammatic genre moved on the same track for book and stone epigrams, this work offers an important contribution to the ongoing debate on the history of the epigrammatic genre and aims to stimulate further reflection on a poetic genre, which, since its origins in the Greek world, has been successful both in ancient and modern literary traditions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEpigrams, GreekxHistory and criticism. 4aDeixis. 4aGriechisches Epigramm. 4aHellenistische Dichtung. 4aInschrift. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z97831107668200 cEPUBz97831106818570 cprintz978311068159840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311068167340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110681673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110681673/original  a978-3-11-076682-0  DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK